s or her "self," an entirely novel experience for many of them—had their antecedents in the Orthodox Christian practices of doing penance in the public gaze. Individualization in Soviet Russia occurred through the intensification of these public penitential practices rather than the private confessional practices that are characteristic of Western Christianity. He also finds that objectification of the individual in Russia relied on practices of mutual surveillance among peers, rather than on the hierarchical surveillance of subordinates by superiors that characterized the West. The implications of this book expand well beyond its brilliant analysis of the connection between Bolshevism and Eastern Orthodoxy to shed light on many questions about the nature of Russian society and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNational characteristics, Russian. 0aPolitical culturezSoviet Union. 0aRussians. 0aSocial controlzSoviet Union. 0aSocial psychologyzSoviet Union. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  abolshevism.  acommunist.  aeastern orthodoxy.  afall of gorbachev.  ahierarchical surveillance.  aindividualization.  aintensification.  akharkhordin.  amichel foucault.  anovel experience.  aorthodox christian.  aparty rituals.  aprivate confessional practices.  apublic gaze.  apublic penitential practices.  arussia.  arussian revolution.  arussian society.  asoviet individual.  asoviet russia.  asurveillance.  awestern christianity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021604440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520921801?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520921801423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520921801/original  